--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DETAILED LAYER BREAKDOWN
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LAYER 1: THE FOUNDATION LAYER (SimPy Primitives)
- Description: The runtime engine provided by the core SimPy library.
- Components:  `simpy.Environment` and `simpy.Container`.
- Responsibility: Handles the simulation clock (env.now), manages the event loop 
  queue, and ensures that process steps execute at the exact microsecond 
  required without time-slippage.

LAYER 2: THE PHYSICAL NODE LAYER (Assets)
- Description: The structural nodes of the supply chain network.
- Component:   `StorageTank` Class.
- Responsibility: Tracks state-specific variables (mass, density, max working 
  capacity, free space available) at a distinct physical location. 
- Design Principle: Nodes are anonymous and passive. A tank does not know where 
  its material originates or where it is going; it only manages its internal 
  volumetric limits (including the 95% safety working volume rule).

LAYER 3: THE EDGE LAYER (Flows & Transformation)
- Description: The dynamic lines connecting the physical nodes.
- Components:  `ProductionProcess` and `TransportLink` Classes.
- Responsibility: Governs the movement and physical transformation of material 
  over time. 
  * ProductionProcess transfers material continuously between a generic 
    source_node and dest_node while calculating process yields.
  * TransportLink handles discrete batch logistics (e.g., road truck cycles) 
    and handles queueing/demurrage if a destination node is full.

LAYER 4: THE CONTROL LAYER (Business Logic & Orchestration)
- Description: The operational brain of the manufacturing layout.
- Component:   `CampaignController` Class.
- Responsibility: Monitors asset conditions in Layer 2 and dynamically toggles 
  the active execution status of flow processes in Layer 3.
- Design Principle: Separates manufacturing capability from scheduling policy. 
  Campaign rules (e.g., triggering a chemical run when a buffer tank hits 95% 
  capacity) can be modified without altering the underlying process code.

LAYER 5: THE OBSERVER LAYER (Telemetry & Output)
- Description: The data logging system operating parallel to the plant.
- Component:   `TelemetryEngine` Class.
- Responsibility: Interrogates the network nodes at a fixed interval (every 
  simulation hour), captures inventory snapshots, and compiles data frames into 
  an exportable CSV file.
- Design Principle: Prevents telemetry code from polluting the core business 
  logic of tanks and pipelines.

LAYER 6: THE CONFIGURATION LAYER (The Pipeline Setup)
- Description: The entry point block (`if __name__ == "__main__":`).
- Responsibility: Defines the concrete simulation context. Instantiates specific 
  tanks, declares physical constraints (m³, densities, flow rates), wires edges 
  to nodes, attaches controllers, and executes the environment runtime.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SUMMARY ANALOGY: THE BUCKET MODEL
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Layer 1: Gravity and Time (The physical laws of the simulation).
- Layer 2: The Buckets (Physical storage holding the inventory).
- Layer 3: The Hoses (The pipelines and transport links moving fluid).
- Layer 4: The Valve Operator (The scheduler opening and closing flows).
- Layer 5: The Inspector (The clipboard holder taking hourly level readings).
- Layer 6: The Factory Floor Blueprint (Deciding where to connect each hose).

